      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Anxiety-related stress eating is when you turn to food specifically in response to anxious feelings, worry, or overwhelm. Unlike general emotional eating, it's triggered by anxiety symptoms like racing thoughts, future worries, or a sense of impending doom. Food becomes a way to temporarily calm the nervous system."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do I eat more when I'm anxious?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Anxiety activates your body's stress response, releasing cortisol which can increase appetite. Eating also triggers the parasympathetic nervous system (rest and digest), which temporarily counteracts the anxiety response. Your brain learns that food provides relief, creating a cycle of anxiety → eating → temporary calm."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How is anxiety eating different from regular emotional eating?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "While all emotional eating involves using food to cope with feelings, anxiety eating is specifically triggered by worry, fear, and overwhelm. It often comes with physical symptoms like restlessness, racing heart, or tension. The eating is an attempt to calm the nervous system rather than comfort sadness or fill boredom."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can EmotionEat help with anxiety eating?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. EmotionEat helps you identify when anxiety is driving your eating through daily check-in conversations. The AI recognizes anxiety patterns, helps you understand your specific triggers, and offers personalized grounding strategies to interrupt the anxiety-eating cycle before it takes hold."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will this app help me feel less anxious?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "EmotionEat is designed to help you understand the connection between anxiety and eating, not to treat anxiety itself. However, many users find that building awareness of their patterns and having grounding strategies reduces both anxiety eating and overall anxiety levels. For clinical anxiety, please consult a healthcare professional."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is my data private and secure?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Absolutely. EmotionEat uses bank-level encryption to protect your conversations and data. We never sell or share your personal information with third parties. Your emotional journey stays completely private."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How quickly can I see results with anxiety eating?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Many users start recognizing their anxiety-eating patterns within the first week. Learning to interrupt the cycle typically takes 2-4 weeks of consistent daily check-ins. The key is building awareness so you can catch anxiety before it leads to eating."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is EmotionEat free to use?",
